notes.body:
An old Mexican couple.
They look like it, oh so much.
He with a straw hat a furred leather jacket, and a metal cane.

She with a pretty green dress, the hair combed back tightly. The look fierce and with teeth gapping.

Their skins are brown. Really brown, the sun kind of, with all the wrinkles that come from age and work outside.

They are seated in blue strollers, pushed along by airport personnel.
The carts look like shopping carts, but the way they seat themselves on these tolling chairs makes them look like thrones.

The King and the Queen of Mexico.

Standing sitting in line for admission.
notes.title: An old Mexican couple.

notes.body:
Ancestry is really a big deal here.
Today I had a homeless woman tracing me her origins back to Budapest, Estonia, Mexico, Native Americans, the Huns and an old wealthy Jewish family in general.
There's ads to discover your roots using genetics on TV.
Not just one.
And people are fast to tell you that they are '1/8th Kraut' or '1/16th French'.
notes.title: Ancestry is really a big deal here.

notes.body:
And for hours, during this one ride,
I used to sit and watch out of the window...
I just could and cannot understand how slow we are moving about the map.

Of course: we're moving fast, oh yes we are
But the outside is not.
The outside moves very slow.

'We just left the valley and now there will be miles and miles of oak trees, before we start entering the pine tree area...'

The landscape changes slowly.
These same grasslands, these same hills, these same oak trees.

It's a big country.
Too big for little me to comprehend.

And then there's houses all along the way.
Not all along. A lot is empty.
But there are houses here.
And houses there.
People call this place home.
And other people that place.

All these lives...
I just can't get it.
notes.title: And for hours, during this one ride,
